title: National public spending during COVID spiked and ‘never came back down’
description: Nationals Senator Matt Canavan says spending during COVID-19 spiked and never came back down.  “Of course we did have spending … keep things going during COVID,” Mr Canavan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “It just never came back down.”

title: ‘Before she went’: Leaked Opposition migration plan analysed
description: Sky News host Paul Murray analyses the leaked Opposition immigration crackdown plan under former Liberal Party leader Sussan Ley.  “The Opposition is not saying it is the playbook,” Mr Murray said.  “But apparently it was one Sussan Ley was thinking about before she went.”

title: ‘Some level of discrimination’: Ley-era migration crackdown proposal analysed
description: Sky News host Paul Murray analyses the proposed ban on immigration from specific countries where it is run by a “terrorist”.  “Let’s talk here about the back and forth today,” Mr Murray said.  “In and around banning certain people from certain countries and certain areas.”

title: Jim Chalmers rejects plan for bipartisan budget taskforce
description: Sky News host Paul Murray analyses how treasurer Jim Chalmers has rejected the proposal to create a bipartisan budget taskforce.  “While the lights won’t turn off anytime soon,” Mr Murray said.  “Debt goes from being the 10th biggest thing we spend on the budget … into the top five.”

title: ‘Potential criminal behaviour’: Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor ‘not immune from prosecution’
description: TalkTV host Mark Dolan says Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor is not immune from prosecution, claiming the former prince allegedly shared market-sensitive government data with nations around the world when he was a trade envoy for the UK.   “Brittain's chief prosecutor has said no one is above the law, including Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor,” Mr Dolan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “He’s not immune from prosecution, and the most serious allegation against him at the moment in terms of his potential criminal behaviour is his time as a trade envoy for a decade representing the UK government.”

title: UK’s social media crackdown labelled a ‘distraction’ for Keir Starmer
description: TalkTV host Mark Dolan says the UK’s social media crackdown is a distraction for UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer.   “It’s been obviously well intentioned this move in Australia … it’s been successful to a degree … maybe 5 million accounts have been shut down that were owned by or set up for under 16s,” Mr Dolan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “I think this is a distraction for Keir Starmer.”

title: Taylor pitches bipartisan taskforce to tackle government spending
description: Sky News host Paul Murray analyses Liberal Party Leader Angus Taylor pitching a bipartisan taskforce on government spending.  “Now, at a barbecue, this is what everybody wants,” Mr Murray said.  “Every three years they have to go to war with each other to try to hold onto or to take power but why not this as an idea?”

title: ‘Actions are hard’: TV host urges Angus Taylor to take ‘real action’ on immigration
description: Sky News host Andrew Bolt urges Opposition Leader Angus Taylor to take “real action” on immigration.   “Angus Taylor knows that he also has to fight Pauline Hanson's One Nation on Australian values, and especially immigration,” Mr Bolt said.   “Slogans are easy. Actions are hard.  “Since Taylor's big win over Sussan Ley on Friday, he's said again and again he won't just cut immigration but stop certain kinds of immigrants coming here.”

title: ‘Aliens are real’: Obama nods to confirmation of alien life
description: Sky News host James Macpherson analyses former US president Barack Obama claiming “aliens are real”.  “He did not hesitate to affirm their existence,” Mr Macpherson said.  “When asked during a podcast interview at the weekend.”

title: New South Wales to overhaul approach to bullying
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond highlights New South Wales’ new approach to bullying.  “Speaking of alien life forms,” Mr Bond said.  “Certainly, the way they behave is somewhat alien to most of us. Bullies.”

title: Hillary Clinton boasts more deportations under Bill Clinton and Barack Obama than Trump
description: Sky News host James Macpherson highlights comments from Hillary Clinton in Germany claiming higher illegal immigration handling prior to Donald Trump.  Ms Clinton stated more people were deported under Bill Clinton and Barack Obama without ‘killing citizens’.  “She is boasting that Clinton and Obama deported more than Trump,” Mr Macpherson said.

title: Scientist gives himself brain damage attempting to disprove ‘Havana Syndrome’
description: Sky News host Freya Leach highlights how a scientist in Norway has given himself brain damage attempting to disprove ‘Havana Syndrome’.  “A scientist from Norway was determined to prove that the Havana Syndrome, which is this mysterious sickness being reported by US diplomats,” Ms Leach said.  “That it was fake, it didn’t come from one of these discombobulator machines … so he got one of these machines and tested it out on himself and gave himself brain damage.”

title: ‘Not little green men’: Obama scrutinised over knowledge of extraterrestrial life
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond questions former US president Barack Obama claiming “aliens exist”.  “I suspect they are not little green men,” Mr Bond said.  “Surely there is some kind of life form somewhere else in the universe.”

title: US military footage of ‘purported UFOs’ analysed
description: Sky News host James Macpherson highlights how the United States military released footage of “UFOs” in 2020.  “The US military released some footage of purported UFOs a while back,” Mr Macpherson said.  “Ronald Reagan said he would not be surprised if evidence for alien life was found.”

title: Italian police launch investigation over ‘ugly’ building
description: Sky News host James Macpherson says police in Italy have launched an investigation into how a building “so ugly” was ever approved.  “Florence is one of the most beautiful cities in the world,” Mr Macpherson said.  “Which makes this next story particularly interesting.”
